Program Implementation Description : The HIV/AIDS Round 7 grant for the West Bank and the Gaza Strip aims to help attain the Millennium Development Goal (MDG) related to combating HIV/AIDS through halting and reversing the spread of HIV infection by 2015.  It focuses on improving the prevention and reducing the vulnerability to HIV infection, enhancing capacities for provision of professional treatment and care for HIV positive patients and strengthening coordination, management and partnerships for an enhanced and consolidated HIV response. The specific goals of the grant include halting the spread of HIV and STIs (Sexually transmitted infections) amongst the most at risk populations and the general public and improving the quality of life for people living with and affected by HIV/AIDS. 

These broad goals will be achieved through three key objectives namely: 
I.	Strengthen community action to maintain low HIV prevalence particularly among populations most at risk and vulnerable in partnership with NGOs.
II.	Reduce morbidity and mortality through improved access to treatment, care and psycho-social support to those infected and affected.
III.	Reinforce capacities, partnerships, coordination, monitoring and evaluation of the national response in line with the three ones.

Country: West Bank and Gaza Strip

Program Title: Future Hope: Scaling up universal access to prevention, treatment and care in the West Bank and Gaza Strip

Principal Recipient: United Nations Development Programme – Program of Assistance for the Palestinian People  (UNDP-PAPP)

Planned Activities:
•	Mass media campaigns addressing all aspects of HIV/AIDS and journalist training for  improved HIV/AIDS reporting;
•	Distribution of condoms to most at risk population groups; 
•	Training of health and social service workers for counseling and testing;
•	Training of health service providers in STI syndromic case management; 
•	Sensitization of political, ministerial, community and religious leaders to improve their Commitment to the fight against HIV/AIDS;
•	Strengthening of  laboratory, health and social services; and
•	Conducting of sero-prevalence and Knowledge, Attitude, Practices and Behavior (KAPB) surveys.

