Program Title: Quality DOTS implementation in West Bank and in the Gaza Strip

Principal Recipient: United Nations Development Programme – Programme of Assistance to the Palestinian People

Goal: To reduce the burden and maintain a low transmission level of TB (tuberculosis) in the West Bank and Gaza, particularly among vulnerable groups including the disadvantaged, refugees and Bedouin communities by 2015 in line with the Millennium Development Goals and the Stop TB Partnership targets.

Target Group/Beneficiaries:
• Bedouin populations;
• Refugees;
• Migrants; and
• Socially and economically disadvantaged groups.

Strategies:
• Strengthen program management capacity in West Bank and the Gaza Strip;
• Pursue high quality DOTS (Directly Observed Treatment, Short-course) expansion
and enhancement;
• Address major challenges such as access to services for refugees and Bedouin
populations and contact tracing; and
• Enable and promote research.

Planned Activities:
• Develop TB medical guidelines and TB laboratory guidelines;
• Develop a mid-term TB strategic plan with a plan of action to be updated yearly;
• Arrange regular supervision visits to health centers in the West Bank and the Gaza Strip;
• Conduct a drug resistance survey among all new and treated TB cases;
• Revise the TB recording and reporting system;
• Expand DOTS to an additional four districts in the Gaza Strip and seven districts in the West Bank in the first two years of the program and pursue high quality DOTS among Bedouin populations and refugees;
• Provide TB drugs and diagnosis;
• Conduct External Quality Assurance and rehabilitation of national central laboratories;
• Develop guidelines on TB contact investigation activities; and
• Operational research: TB data analysis on social determinants of TB and on geographical origin and main population groups.

